    {
      "id": "FN7XHJKjsxFFF7gdiX92w",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1181.8037801713417,
      "y": 80393.96974580291,
      "width": 1050.7193603515625,
      "height": 149.25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "blW",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1270613795,
      "version": 610,
      "versionNonce": 489745806,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646398,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Till now we were doing all things with Docker commands.\nNow came a new way we will write all these commands inside a file, and we will call that file\nas dockerfile. This is also being run by CLI, commands are also being run by CLI. And if it is\ndone in CLI, We can write Python Script or Shell Script or any kind of script.\nWhy do we need to learn, understand and write a different kind of file for it, rather than doing\nbasic scripting.",
      "fontSize": 19.9,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Till now we were doing all things with Docker commands.\nNow came a new way we will write all these commands inside a file, and we will call that file\nas dockerfile. This is also being run by CLI, commands are also being run by CLI. And if it is\ndone in CLI, We can write Python Script or Shell Script or any kind of script.\nWhy do we need to learn, understand and write a different kind of file for it, rather than doing\nbasic scripting.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "-MjQljvy1iDr4fq9HBiyR",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1181.5615926713417,
      "y": 80564.06349580291,
      "width": 176,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "blX",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1384247587,
      "version": 22,
      "versionNonce": 1019804242,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646398,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Why dockerfile ?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Why dockerfile ?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "gAmyC-vlRiuAb0t218Ytx",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1242.9287801713417,
      "y": 80623.39943330291,
      "width": 1111,
      "height": 325,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "blZ",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1074905197,
      "version": 754,
      "versionNonce": 202902478,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646398,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "lets say we have a ubuntu container running in background -dlt\nthen we are installing python server\nexec install ws\nlets say one more exec that will setup post and firewall \nother exec command this will pull website code from Github\n\nand all these things are linux commands, all these things can be scripted, ultimate output is we will\nget a container\n\nFrom this container we can run another command as a part of this script only that will make a image\nNow we know the command to make a image from a container. So we have a image also\n\ndockerfile is a way of creating a image with all these modifications.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "lets say we have a ubuntu container running in background -dlt\nthen we are installing python server\nexec install ws\nlets say one more exec that will setup post and firewall \nother exec command this will pull website code from Github\n\nand all these things are linux commands, all these things can be scripted, ultimate output is we will\nget a container\n\nFrom this container we can run another command as a part of this script only that will make a image\nNow we know the command to make a image from a container. So we have a image also\n\ndockerfile is a way of creating a image with all these modifications.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Q5dXk6RyMxYqBZmI5Glt9",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1241.5733114213417,
      "y": 80975.25099580291,
      "width": 506,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bla",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 838485229,
      "version": 66,
      "versionNonce": 1780080658,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646398,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Now question is why not script why dockerfile?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Now question is why not script why dockerfile?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "STsq465jbntKaUnvq2n9Z",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1301.0147176713417,
      "y": 81004.70802705291,
      "width": 1144,
      "height": 650,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "blb",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 539076813,
      "version": 2511,
      "versionNonce": 1157718542,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646398,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "when infra development or deployment becomes easy becomes fast, people tend to deploy more\ninfra which means more kind of application or microservices , more versions of applications\neverything is more. When there are multiple kind of application or microservice each one of\nthem lets say its own container or their own image. Each application will have atleast their\nown image, When we have application 1 image, if we will launch a container, my version 1 is out\nor deployed, Version 2 same way we have a image, we will run a container and deploy simple as \nthat, Now the problem is whatever changes we are doint with all these commands who is keeping\na track of what changes are done in which container, there is no track of it Or what changes are\ndone in which image, Each image is modified from its base image, like we pickup a base ubuntu,\nwe modify and modify we make up a new container image. Or we pick up a modified image and we \nmodify it more and pack it as a new image. this always happens but whatever base we are taking\nand whatever modifications we are doing, who is keeping a track of it Noone, \nWe have noticed we have write two ways of making a container or dealing with a image, One thing\nwas when we pack a image to a tar file, Another way was when there was a running container, we \nmake a tar file out of it. From this tar now we will make a image. Both of these will have diff \nof metadata first with metadata another without metadata. Like second way the issue is here we\nhave noone who is keeping track of this. What is happening behind this.\n\nWhen we write a dockerfile and we execute it like a docker command, docker has a way of modifying\nimage in such a way that each change is kept track of. Each change is labeled and keep track of.\nThis is why we use dockerfile.\n\nNow if we have to move from application version 1 to version 2, we can just create dockerfile version1\nand version2, and this version 2 with slightly more changes, and it willl help us to deploy dockerfile\nversion 2. So that part is also very simple. Everything becomes simple here, complete deployment becomes\nsimple here, container management, image management everything becomes free",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "when infra development or deployment becomes easy becomes fast, people tend to deploy more\ninfra which means more kind of application or microservices , more versions of applications\neverything is more. When there are multiple kind of application or microservice each one of\nthem lets say its own container or their own image. Each application will have atleast their\nown image, When we have application 1 image, if we will launch a container, my version 1 is out\nor deployed, Version 2 same way we have a image, we will run a container and deploy simple as \nthat, Now the problem is whatever changes we are doint with all these commands who is keeping\na track of what changes are done in which container, there is no track of it Or what changes are\ndone in which image, Each image is modified from its base image, like we pickup a base ubuntu,\nwe modify and modify we make up a new container image. Or we pick up a modified image and we \nmodify it more and pack it as a new image. this always happens but whatever base we are taking\nand whatever modifications we are doing, who is keeping a track of it Noone, \nWe have noticed we have write two ways of making a container or dealing with a image, One thing\nwas when we pack a image to a tar file, Another way was when there was a running container, we \nmake a tar file out of it. From this tar now we will make a image. Both of these will have diff \nof metadata first with metadata another without metadata. Like second way the issue is here we\nhave noone who is keeping track of this. What is happening behind this.\n\nWhen we write a dockerfile and we execute it like a docker command, docker has a way of modifying\nimage in such a way that each change is kept track of. Each change is labeled and keep track of.\nThis is why we use dockerfile.\n\nNow if we have to move from application version 1 to version 2, we can just create dockerfile version1\nand version2, and this version 2 with slightly more changes, and it willl help us to deploy dockerfile\nversion 2. So that part is also very simple. Everything becomes simple here, complete deployment becomes\nsimple here, container management, image management everything becomes free",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "ueUkJ4dds-trFxtEzP02M",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1302.7803426713417,
      "y": 81675.97755830291,
      "width": 451,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ble",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1695143533,
      "version": 47,
      "versionNonce": 264768978,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646398,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "So what we are creating using dockerfile?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "So what we are creating using dockerfile?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "3CEz5Bp6ze7xP3IGPjg3p",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1342.6123739213417,
      "y": 81701.52833955291,
      "width": 1089,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "blf",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1645406317,
      "version": 891,
      "versionNonce": 988147790,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "we are creating docker images, and using these image we can run run command or something like that\nto create our container.\ndockerfile can be one, In a system in a particular location there can be only one dockerfile, which\ngenerally is that each application has its own dockerfile.\n\nSo when we are working on lets say Project1, this project1 will have its own directory p1 directory\ninside this p1 directory there will be a file called as dockerfile\nthere is another directory p2, this p2 will have its own dockerfile. But in one location, in one\ndirectory there can be only 1 dockerfile that is for sure.\n\nIf there is a case inside p1 directory p2 directory is there, then p1 can have 1 dockerfiile and p2\ncan have another dockerfile, that is allowed.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "we are creating docker images, and using these image we can run run command or something like that\nto create our container.\ndockerfile can be one, In a system in a particular location there can be only one dockerfile, which\ngenerally is that each application has its own dockerfile.\n\nSo when we are working on lets say Project1, this project1 will have its own directory p1 directory\ninside this p1 directory there will be a file called as dockerfile\nthere is another directory p2, this p2 will have its own dockerfile. But in one location, in one\ndirectory there can be only 1 dockerfile that is for sure.\n\nIf there is a case inside p1 directory p2 directory is there, then p1 can have 1 dockerfiile and p2\ncan have another dockerfile, that is allowed.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "nqja5ZZ71WncsOmPgvv7j",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1343.7334676713417,
      "y": 82029.85255830291,
      "width": 319,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "blg",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 339926723,
      "version": 35,
      "versionNonce": 1122665362,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Why Single dockerfile only ->",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Why Single dockerfile only ->",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "RT_kSmWnP3bKXUgMTlnh7",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1392.5420614213417,
      "y": 82058.59865205291,
      "width": 1133,
      "height": 600,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "blh",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1394284867,
      "version": 1345,
      "versionNonce": 429831822,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "due to docker will recognize it by direct filename compulsorily has to be dockerfile. So obviously\nin a single location we can't put multiple file with same name.\n\nmkdir p1\ncd p1\nvi dockerfile -> it should be key and parameter\n                 1 FROM  ubuntu:latest  \n                            from basically takes the input of what base image we want to use, If we are\n                            not having image it will pull, if we are having that, it is going to use\n                            that, this we can write small or cap also , since we want to distinguise\n                            it from the command good to write it is all caps. Just a convention not\n                            a rule.\n                 2 RUN touch f1\n\n                 save and exit this file :wq\n\nNow run this dockerfile, to run the dockerfile or to create a image from this what we have to do is\nrun the docker command\ndocker build -t myubuntu . -> . means location of docker file which is current location\n                                myubuntu is image name, if the dockerfile file is in other\n                                location that we can give .\n\ndocker run -it myubuntu -> run the conatainer\nnow do ls inside container we will see f1 is there.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "due to docker will recognize it by direct filename compulsorily has to be dockerfile. So obviously\nin a single location we can't put multiple file with same name.\n\nmkdir p1\ncd p1\nvi dockerfile -> it should be key and parameter\n                 1 FROM  ubuntu:latest  \n                            from basically takes the input of what base image we want to use, If we are\n                            not having image it will pull, if we are having that, it is going to use\n                            that, this we can write small or cap also , since we want to distinguise\n                            it from the command good to write it is all caps. Just a convention not\n                            a rule.\n                 2 RUN touch f1\n\n                 save and exit this file :wq\n\nNow run this dockerfile, to run the dockerfile or to create a image from this what we have to do is\nrun the docker command\ndocker build -t myubuntu . -> . means location of docker file which is current location\n                                myubuntu is image name, if the dockerfile file is in other\n                                location that we can give .\n\ndocker run -it myubuntu -> run the conatainer\nnow do ls inside container we will see f1 is there.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
