      "seed": 1528128851,
      "version": 4,
      "versionNonce": 63564046,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "ip address ->\n172.17.0.2",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "ip address ->\n172.17.0.2",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "vUOWUtL3RQfPFmp6aWb5c",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1555.7525739605703,
      "y": 88733.45876281739,
      "width": 1144,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bnr",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 121709917,
      "version": 937,
      "versionNonce": 1693415122,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Since they are giving kind of same IP, which means there can be a possible issue, if my user is\nconnecting with ip 172.17.0.2, then which container? this is a issue\n\nHow do we try to solve this?\n    We will try to create a virtual layer in both of hypervisor, and this virtual layer basiclly\nbrings both these docker containers into same network, how it will happend, basically we will create\nfirst docker and we will define this docker as our master and other docker as a slave for this master\nusing this we are defining when anyone container need a IP that will take from master, we can launch\ncontainer using slave also but ip will be issued from master only. when container will ask IP from slave\nslave will redirect it to master and master will give IP.\n\nSo this kind of networking is called as overlay networking.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Since they are giving kind of same IP, which means there can be a possible issue, if my user is\nconnecting with ip 172.17.0.2, then which container? this is a issue\n\nHow do we try to solve this?\n    We will try to create a virtual layer in both of hypervisor, and this virtual layer basiclly\nbrings both these docker containers into same network, how it will happend, basically we will create\nfirst docker and we will define this docker as our master and other docker as a slave for this master\nusing this we are defining when anyone container need a IP that will take from master, we can launch\ncontainer using slave also but ip will be issued from master only. when container will ask IP from slave\nslave will redirect it to master and master will give IP.\n\nSo this kind of networking is called as overlay networking.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "1Sr21qeTY2Tcb0BpD1PJZ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1557.6844564392459,
      "y": 89076.01590724626,
      "width": 352,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bns",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1233855059,
      "version": 36,
      "versionNonce": 1023776590,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How to setup overlay network -> ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How to setup overlay network -> ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "q7aYU2jFL2S-EtrBynIK6",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1618.0926206400884,
      "y": 89099.5463995554,
      "width": 1122,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bnt",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1575474653,
      "version": 1202,
      "versionNonce": 826068114,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Basically we make a cluster of Docker, where in In all these cluster one become my master node and \nother became my worker or slave node. Now Worker or slave now they take IP from master. For this there\nis a concept/tool in docker which is called as docker swam. Problem with docker swam is, It is very\ncomplex to manage, Right now it looks easy becasue we are only discussing for a single application, \nwhen it goes for multiple applications and then multiple system have to share different overlays. One\nis sharing one overlay and others are shareing different overlays, but all are somehow connected \ntogether then it start becoming complex like who is the master who is the slave, everything like that.\nTo simply all of this we have a new tool which is called as kubernetes. In kubernetes one is my master\nand all the other my slave/worker nodes. And no matter what application they are running, how their\nnetworking is managed everythinh is smoothhly done using kubernetes. wherein there is one master and\nmany worker/slave nodes. Due to this we need kubernetes.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Basically we make a cluster of Docker, where in In all these cluster one become my master node and \nother became my worker or slave node. Now Worker or slave now they take IP from master. For this there\nis a concept/tool in docker which is called as docker swam. Problem with docker swam is, It is very\ncomplex to manage, Right now it looks easy becasue we are only discussing for a single application, \nwhen it goes for multiple applications and then multiple system have to share different overlays. One\nis sharing one overlay and others are shareing different overlays, but all are somehow connected \ntogether then it start becoming complex like who is the master who is the slave, everything like that.\nTo simply all of this we have a new tool which is called as kubernetes. In kubernetes one is my master\nand all the other my slave/worker nodes. And no matter what application they are running, how their\nnetworking is managed everythinh is smoothhly done using kubernetes. wherein there is one master and\nmany worker/slave nodes. Due to this we need kubernetes.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "EPOI1PfT5L2yvtl9v4DTY",
