    },
    {
      "id": "jcbPN2q6WubM-FDIDTllD",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1536.9985792205264,
      "y": 89724.04384816092,
      "width": 1320,
      "height": 425,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bo0",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 319530643,
      "version": 1436,
      "versionNonce": 981237202,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "When we setup Vm by ourself, when we setup a VM, we need Oracle Virtual box and we need a ISO file of ubuntu linux.\nor any other linux. Now in this case ISO is a file, When we setup this ISO file inside Oracle virtual box then it \nbecomes a running machine it becomes process.\n\nIn docker also we have the same case that we have a file but this is a different file, this creates containers, this\ncreates chhotu machines and these machines are created by these image files which are docker images and the running\nprocess that they create are my containers. If we will go with this mindset alot of commands will be clear, for example\nwhen we list files in linux we use ls, when we list running process we use ps\n\ndocker ps -> to list all the running containers, Because it is listing running container there are possiblity that there\nare container which are not in running state also, they are either exited or power off or shut down or anyother state.\nif they are in these state and we have to see what all these container whihc we can start and use\n\ndocker ps -a -> it will list all the container no matter in what state\n\ndocker images or docker image ls -> this will give all the image using which we can run a container.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "When we setup Vm by ourself, when we setup a VM, we need Oracle Virtual box and we need a ISO file of ubuntu linux.\nor any other linux. Now in this case ISO is a file, When we setup this ISO file inside Oracle virtual box then it \nbecomes a running machine it becomes process.\n\nIn docker also we have the same case that we have a file but this is a different file, this creates containers, this\ncreates chhotu machines and these machines are created by these image files which are docker images and the running\nprocess that they create are my containers. If we will go with this mindset alot of commands will be clear, for example\nwhen we list files in linux we use ls, when we list running process we use ps\n\ndocker ps -> to list all the running containers, Because it is listing running container there are possiblity that there\nare container which are not in running state also, they are either exited or power off or shut down or anyother state.\nif they are in these state and we have to see what all these container whihc we can start and use\n\ndocker ps -a -> it will list all the container no matter in what state\n\ndocker images or docker image ls -> this will give all the image using which we can run a container.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "9hr14_jG6wojjvsNaElwu",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1540.3630016727998,
      "y": 90189.69301306395,
      "width": 1287,
      "height": 50,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bo1",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 9419955,
      "version": 186,
      "versionNonce": 401637454,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "DockerHub -> public repo for docker images,  we pull the images from here and we can run that image and it will start\n    container as per our specifications.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "DockerHub -> public repo for docker images,  we pull the images from here and we can run that image and it will start\n    container as per our specifications.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "OuQVxciBVFd5jcqKjjQ9Z",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1541.832378388574,
      "y": 90307.95116888244,
      "width": 803,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bo2",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 301397363,
      "version": 79,
      "versionNonce": 2106651538,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "If we dont want to keep my images on dockerhub where else we can keep? ->",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "If we dont want to keep my images on dockerhub where else we can keep? ->",
