      "text": "dockerfile is made up with keyword and their parameters, Interview level questions will come from\nkeywords",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "dockerfile is made up with keyword and their parameters, Interview level questions will come from\nkeywords",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "cbAmWVYCg8RwxJ5xQF-MB",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1494.437786757995,
      "y": 98422.71072946498,
      "width": 1221,
      "height": 400,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bpA",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 595354972,
      "version": 1779,
      "versionNonce": 664536210,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "RUN -> it is executed when our image is being built. For example if I want to install something, update\nsomething, upgrade something we want to do it before final image is created. Because at the final container\nlaunching, if at that time I am installing something or updating my app, it is going to take a lot of time and\ncontainers are suppose to be launch fast. thats why some steps we do while image creation itself\nAt the same time there are other steps, for example our service starting step systemctl start  those step\nwe usually start when our machine is ON, because if the machine is not ON, it will not make any sence. So what\nwe do , we put them to CMD. CMD is basically defines that whenever our machine is starting at that time we are\ngoing to run this command. Same is with one more command here which is ENTRYPOINT, ENTRYPOINT also we use the \ncommand whihc we want to run at the time of machine booting.\nENTRYPOINT is more like CMD we write a command, Now this command can use multiple parameters, those parameters \nare passed by ENTRYPOINT. though we can directly give it in CMD, giving it in ENTRYPOINT make sure that we are\nable to separately see the command and separately see the parameter. and these parameters later on can be taken\nas user input also.\n\ndocker run -idt myimage:latest -firstparameter -secondparameter -soon -> these parameters will be taken by\n                our dockerfile inside ENTRYPOINT or CMD",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "RUN -> it is executed when our image is being built. For example if I want to install something, update\nsomething, upgrade something we want to do it before final image is created. Because at the final container\nlaunching, if at that time I am installing something or updating my app, it is going to take a lot of time and\ncontainers are suppose to be launch fast. thats why some steps we do while image creation itself\nAt the same time there are other steps, for example our service starting step systemctl start  those step\nwe usually start when our machine is ON, because if the machine is not ON, it will not make any sence. So what\nwe do , we put them to CMD. CMD is basically defines that whenever our machine is starting at that time we are\ngoing to run this command. Same is with one more command here which is ENTRYPOINT, ENTRYPOINT also we use the \ncommand whihc we want to run at the time of machine booting.\nENTRYPOINT is more like CMD we write a command, Now this command can use multiple parameters, those parameters \nare passed by ENTRYPOINT. though we can directly give it in CMD, giving it in ENTRYPOINT make sure that we are\nable to separately see the command and separately see the parameter. and these parameters later on can be taken\nas user input also.\n\ndocker run -idt myimage:latest -firstparameter -secondparameter -soon -> these parameters will be taken by\n                our dockerfile inside ENTRYPOINT or CMD",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "o88cmAaSKDojhtRrjVvE_",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1513.351849257995,
      "y": 98922.15604196498,
      "width": 968,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bpB",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 963612260,
      "version": 106,
      "versionNonce": 864142734,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "What are the Three ways to reduce the size of dockerfile(final image that is generated)?",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "What are the Three ways to reduce the size of dockerfile(final image that is generated)?",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "GA87fkHcxosRbzBRqHm97",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1568.504193007995,
      "y": 98944.40213571498,
      "width": 440,
      "height": 75,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bpC",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1429502812,
      "version": 138,
      "versionNonce": 311534162,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1777685646399,
      "link": null,
